---
// Static comparison page — no JS needed, pure server-rendered HTML
---

<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <title>Astro vs Next.js — Comparison</title>
  <style>
    body { font-family: Arial, sans-serif; padding: 2rem; max-width: 800px; }
    table { border-collapse: collapse; width: 100%; font-size: 0.9rem; }
    th, td { padding: 0.6rem 1rem; border: 1px solid #e2e8f0; text-align: left; }
    th { background: #f7fafc; font-weight: 600; }
    .good { color: #276749; }
    .neutral { color: #744210; }
    .bad { color: #c53030; }
  </style>
</head>
<body>
  <h1>Astro vs Next.js</h1>
  <p>Both are full-stack JS frameworks with SSR, but they have different default philosophies.</p>

  <table>
    <thead>
      <tr>
        <th>Feature</th>
        <th>Astro</th>
        <th>Next.js</th>
      </tr>
    </thead>
    <tbody>
      <tr>
        <td>Default rendering</td>
        <td class="good">Static HTML, zero JS</td>
        <td class="neutral">Server Components (React tree)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>JS shipped by default</td>
        <td class="good">Zero (opt-in per island)</td>
        <td class="neutral">React runtime + page bundle</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Interactivity model</td>
        <td>Islands (partial hydration)</td>
        <td>Full React tree (selective with RSC)</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Framework support</td>
        <td class="good">React, Vue, Svelte, Solid (mix)</td>
        <td>React only</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>API routes</td>
        <td class="neutral">Endpoints (not full server)</td>
        <td class="good">Full API routes + Server Actions</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Best for</td>
        <td>Content-heavy sites, blogs, docs</td>
        <td>Apps with lots of interactivity</td>
      </tr>
      <tr>
        <td>Data fetching</td>
        <td>Top-level await in .astro files</td>
        <td>fetch() in Server Components</td>
      </tr>
    </tbody>
  </table>

  <p style="margin-top:1.5rem; font-size:0.85rem; color:#555">
    Rule of thumb: choose Astro for marketing sites, docs, and blogs where most content is static.
    Choose Next.js for apps that need a lot of client-side state and complex data flows.
  </p>
</body>
</html>
